Jon Stiles wrote:
> For a type 4 motor. If you clean the galleys and pushrod tubes and make sure
> the pushrod tubes are not bent or dented at the ends, all you need is a
> little motor oil to slip them into place.

This is what I did when I first rebuilt the engine, and now 60,000 miles 
later it's leaking all over.

You can use a small amount of
> aviation gasket sealer, but no silicone is needed. Mine don't leak after
> about 10K miles of mixed driving and I didn't use anything at all.

I was thinking the same, but my mechanic had suggested the silicone.  He 
does use the aviation sealer for the engine case and the valve covers, 
but he was pretty specific about the silicone on the pushrod seals.... hmm..

It's a type4, btw.
